## NO ACADEMIC OR PSYCHOLOGICAL JARGON IN USER-FACING COPY

KinMatch is informed by behavioral science research (Aron, Reis 
& Shaver, Gable, Dunbar, etc.) — but users should NEVER see this 
vocabulary in the product. Researcher names, framework labels, 
and clinical terminology stay in internal documentation only.

Banned in user-facing copy:
- "Aron-style," "disclosure," "vulnerability disclosure"
- "Capitalization," "active capitalization"
- "Self-disclosure," "reciprocal disclosure"
- "Intimacy process model," "intimacy progression"
- "Friendship maintenance behaviors"
- "Tier 1/2/3 questions," "depth tier"
- "Closeness questions," "relationship maintenance"

The "why this works" line in discovery cards should sound like a 
thoughtful friend giving you confidence to send the message — 
not like a behavioral science textbook explaining a study.

❌ "Aron-style light disclosure. Lets them share what they want."
✓ "Low-stakes and easy to answer. Gives them room to share."

❌ "Capitalization moment — celebrating wins builds trust."
✓ "Wins are worth celebrating. They'll feel good you noticed."

❌ "Tier 3 vulnerability question — only safe after trust-building."
✓ "A deep question. Save it for someone you really want to see."

When in doubt: would a thoughtful friend say this, or would a 
psychology professor say this? If it's the professor, rewrite.

